Azure Security refers to the set of tools, services, and practices used to protect data, applications, and infrastructure in the Azure cloud. Microsoft provides built-in security features at multiple levels including physical, network, identity, and application layers.

Azure follows a shared responsibility model where Microsoft secures the cloud infrastructure, while users are responsible for securing their data and configurations.

For example, Microsoft ensures the physical security of data centers, while users must configure firewalls and access controls.

A real-life use case is an enterprise hosting sensitive customer data. They must implement encryption, access control, and monitoring to prevent breaches.

Another example is startups deploying applications securely using Azure’s built-in tools like firewalls, DDoS protection, and identity services.

Understanding Azure security is critical for protecting systems from cyber threats and ensuring compliance.
